Cultural tourism alongside agriculture are seen as main sectors that have potential for economic development and employment generation in the Northern part of Kosovo. 
Fortress Zvecan one of the oldest Balkan fortresses, lake Gazivode in Zubin Potok, monastery and spa Banjska in Zvecan municipality, Spring health centre  Vuca, Roman-Gallic-City, are only some interesting destinations located in the northern part of Kosovo, which are worth seeing. In this region there is a huge potential for traditional tourism programs such as mountain tourism, historic sites, hiking, hunting and fishing activities which can be considered as key potential areas for sustainable local economic development. To support this potential, we are planning to increase economic development and employment in North Kosovo by improving touristic services through the upgrade of municipal infrastructure, by improving skills and perspectives of youth and women, by promoting Nonrth Kosovo as a tourist destination. This will improve living conditions of the population in the areas targeted by the project and will contribute to the reduction of development disparities among Kosovo municipalities and regions. 
This region offers more possibilities for rural tourism development than any other in Kosovo. This fact is based on a territory surface which is covered by forests varying from 400 to 2,000 meters above the sea level. These forests offer possibilities for development of many summer recreational activities, but are also suitable for winter tourism. An example for all is the locality of Belo Brdo, on the southeast side of Kopaonik Mountain. 
Besides many possibilities for development of winter sports, the area is also rich in thermo mineral water springs, which offer many possibilities for the development of rehabilitation and health tourism. Areas which are subject to spatial planning and special protection are Belo Brdo tourist centre, and Vuca Spa spring and Banjska complex. Village tourism is unfortunately not very developed in this area even if there is a great potential for its development, due to its unpolluted environment, its far distance from city centres, appropriate sea-level height, homemade food, natural water, and more. The road network (macadam and asphalt) in the main localities for tourism development already exists, as well as the power supply network, which allow for further development and improvement of tourism. Projects for development of winter, summer and health tourism have been drafted, but so far nothing has been invested.

Illustrative ideas regarding summer tourism that could be discussed in the Regional Tourism Working Group are: Ibar River Rafting with full-equipped boats that could be organised in cooperation with highly experienced kayakers, riding schools, walking and mountain-bike tours, paragliding schools, sports camps, alpinism courses, building of artificial rocks for climbing, Roman Settlements and Monasteries tours etc. 

The challenge of the project (and other initiatives that promote tourism in North Kosovo) is to connect this potential with the local and regional population as well as international population living and working in Kosovo who seek to explore attractions within Kosovo. The project can address certain issues (better offers, better services and better promotion), while other aspects are beyond the reach of the project team.

The public sector is shrinking, reducing formal employment while there is an increasing number of graduates, woman and other vulnerable groups looking for employment especially those within community and in the country at large.In addition, people are not willing to take the risk to become entrepreneurs, because they have no role models, there is a misconception about entrepreneurship which is seen as a second choice compared to formal employment, people prefer to rely on formal jobs.   In addition, there is limited support to develop entrepreneurship skills. Finally, increasing number of jobless people becomes a burden on the government.

To date, ADC has focused on grass roots, cooperative development and supporting the entrepreneurship hub.  ADC has done this by working with other partners (e.g. to access the cooperatives). The cooperatives and entrepreneurs who have begun work dont have the skills and experience with implementation of their business models to help them to grow and employ others. Whereas, AERG is focusing on supporting graduates and ongoing students in universities to prepare young people for the life after school to become entrepreneurs but also increase the chance of producing employability candidates through different programmes including internship on-job training for non entrepreneurs. Both AERG and ADC work young people both in schools and drop-outs. In the selection of target beneficiaries, emphasis is given to existing companies with growth potential. Further, In the selection of target beneficiaries, emphasis is given to existing companies especially in Kigali province with potential growth. In additional, special attention is given to women entrepreneurs who are expected to constitute at least 60% of direct beneficiaries of our services 
Presently, youth both educates and un educated are not accessing the critically needed support needed to build their skills and expand their business ideas. In addition, youth need more than training and education to build sustainable and innovative businesses  but mentorship, networking, and business guidance too. It is only by addressing each of the challenges facing them  be it extreme poverty, lack of skills and guidance, and capital  that youth will be empowered to start businesses or access quality employment. 
In order to achieve the long term development goals, the Government of Rwanda has formulated a medium strategy. The economic development and poverty reduction strategy (EDPRS 2)s highest priority is growth acceleration and poverty Reduction through its four thematic areas; Economic transformation, Rural development, Productivity and Youth employment as well as accountable governance.
EDPRS 2 aims to achieve the following goals by 2018
Increasing GDP per capital to $ 1000
Reducing the poverty rate to below 30%
Reducing extreme poverty rate below 9%
Quoting from World Bank report 2014.

PROPOSED SOLUTION

Strengthening the hub and expanding AERG business centre and developing internal systems
Create a one stop centre to support various products and services in the value chain, e.g. market information, Business to Business starting with one of the Kigali City district and replicate experiences to all 30 districts of Rwanda. Develop EH Web Site and other promotional materials to make the services known and accessed by the public; Build the capacities of the hub staff through attending professional trainings; Develop a five year strategic business plan for the EH; Develop Entrepreneurship Hub management systems and professional trainings for EH staff. Be a source of information: This will include having business in a box kit for products/services, we will start with 5 kits in line with Kicukiro District priority sector/Cluster namely Weaving/Handcraft, Meat processing, Furniture, Juice-Maize agro-processing and Coffee. 


Contributing to poverty Alleviation: This will be achieved through youth enterprise promotion;  Growing Enterprises access new markets and expansion funding; training women Entrepreneurs on tax education, using IT and internet for tax declaration and  accessing markets and improve Financial Reports; conducting  Business opportunity/inspirational symposia/networking events bringing together various stakeholders including investors/entrepreneurs.  Training growing enterprises on accounting, Financial management among other areas of business management. Moreover, organize fund raising activities for the start-up entrepreneurs to access Technical Assistance and meeting initial start-up costs.

This proposal will have a long term impact in terms of contributing to the Rwanda Economic Development and Poverty Reduction Strategy (EDPRS II) targeting to achieve 11.5% average GDP growth per annum and reduce poverty to below 30%.  This proposal will contribute to governments efforts to transform the economy, the private sector and alleviating constraints to growth of investment by developing the appropriate skills and competencies to allow Rwandan particularly the youth and Women to become more productive and competitive.

Formal Employment: SPARK beneficiaries who acquire a formal job (i.e. sign an employment contract), after receiving SPARK’s support (e.g. employability training). Informal Employment: SPARK beneficiaries who acquire a job in the formal or informal sector, but do not have a regular employment contract, after receiving SPARK’s support (e.g. employability training). Formal job in formal business: Work position, formalised by an employment contract, which has a minimum duration of 6 months and is created in a formal business, which is a start-up or an existing business that grew (and thereby is able to employ more people). Informal job in formal business: Work position, not formalised by an employment contract, has a minimum duration of 6 months and is created in a formal business. The formal business can be a start-up or an existing business that grew (and thereby is able to employ more people).
